<subSubSection id="49C942EEFFFE3926EBD2C50EFCE659FA" pageId="80" pageNumber="81" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="016C1165FFFE3926EBD2C50EFEAA5961" blockId="80.[227,341,573,599]" box="[227,341,573,599]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">
<heading id="5A24A609FFFE3926EBD2C50EFEAA5961" bold="true" box="[227,341,573,599]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="80" pageNumber="81" reason="3">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FFFE3926EBD2C50EFEAA5961" bold="true" box="[227,341,573,599]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="016C1165FFFE3926EBD2C55FFCE659FA" blockId="80.[227,1437,619,716]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">
Two specimens belong to the family 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FFFE3926E99FC558FCA459B3" authorityName="Poey" authorityYear="1861" box="[686,859,619,645]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Malacanthidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="80" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Malacanthidae</taxonomicName>
from the Weches Formation of 
<collectingRegion id="C317DF87FFFE3926EFDBC55FFAD159B0" box="[1258,1326,620,646]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">Texas</collectingRegion>
but lack sufficient diagnostic features; however, they have a shorter posterior part and slightly deeper otolith height and might be different from “ 
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FFFE3926E9BCC581FD6259FD" box="[653,669,690,715]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">L</emphasis>
” 
<taxonomicName id="C6D36AE6FFFE3926E983C581FCED59FA" authorityName="Koken" authorityYear="1888" box="[690,786,690,716]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sciaenidae" genus="Otolithus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="80" pageNumber="81" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sulcatus">
<emphasis id="33A7CD77FFFE3926E983C581FCED59FA" box="[690,786,690,716]" italics="true" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">sulcatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
